<h2>Determine Your Budget</h2>

<p>
Before applying for a mortgage, determine how much house you can actually
afford. Lenders evaluate your Debt-to-Income (DTI) ratio to decide whether
you qualify for a loan.
</p>

<h3>Debt-to-Income Ratio</h3>

<p>
Your DTI ratio compares your monthly debt payments with your monthly gross
income. Most lenders prefer a DTI below 43%, although lower is always better.
Reducing existing loans and credit card balances before applying can improve
your approval chances.
</p>

<h3>Down Payment Matters</h3>

<p>
A larger down payment reduces the lender's risk and often qualifies you for
a lower interest rate. Putting down at least 20% also helps you avoid
Private Mortgage Insurance (PMI).
</p>

