<h2>Get Pre-Approved</h2>

<p>
A mortgage pre-approval shows sellers that you're a serious buyer. During
pre-approval, lenders verify your income, employment, assets, and credit
history before giving you an estimated loan amount.
</p>

<h3>Documents You'll Need</h3>

<ul>
<li>Government-issued ID</li>
<li>Recent pay stubs</li>
<li>Two years of tax returns</li>
<li>Bank statements</li>
<li>Employment verification</li>
<li>Investment account statements</li>
</ul>

<h2>Loan Estimate and Closing Costs</h2>

<p>
Always review your Loan Estimate carefully before accepting a mortgage.
Compare interest rates, lender fees, appraisal fees, title charges, and
closing costs.
</p>

<h3>Watch Out for Hidden Fees</h3>

<ul>
<li>Origination fees</li>
<li>Application fees</li>
<li>Processing fees</li>
<li>Document preparation fees</li>
<li>Underwriting fees</li>
</ul>

<h2>Lock Your Mortgage Rate</h2>

<p>
If interest rates begin rising, consider locking your mortgage rate. A rate
lock protects you from market increases while your loan is being processed.
Ask your lender how long your rate lock remains valid before closing.
</p>

<h2>Discount Points</h2>

<p>
Discount points allow borrowers to pay money upfront in exchange for a lower
interest rate. This option is usually worthwhile if you plan to stay in your
home for many years.
</p>
